    "keyLearningPoints": [
      "ACE-I angioedema is BRADYKININ-mediated, not histamine-mediated \u2014 antihistamines, steroids, and epinephrine have LIMITED or NO effect",
      "Key distinguishing feature: angioedema WITHOUT urticaria (no hives, no itching)",
      "Can occur at ANY time during ACE-I therapy \u2014 25% of cases occur after >1 year of use",
      "Affects lips, tongue, and floor of mouth preferentially \u2014 airway compromise is the primary danger",
      "Treatment: stop ACE-I permanently, supportive care, consider icatibant (bradykinin B2 receptor antagonist) or C1-esterase inhibitor concentrate",
      "African Americans have 3-5x higher incidence \u2014 always consider in this population"
    ],
    "mustNotMiss": [
      "Anaphylaxis (has urticaria, pruritus, wheezing, hypotension \u2014 GIVE EPINEPHRINE)",
      "Hereditary Angioedema (HAE) \u2014 check C4 level, family history, recurrent episodes without ACE-I",
      "Ludwig angina (submandibular space infection \u2014 fever, dental source, neck firmness)",
      "Peritonsillar abscess (trismus, uvular deviation, unilateral)",
      "Airway compromise requiring intubation (have backup plan: surgical airway)"
    ],
    "commonPitfalls": [
      "Treating ACE-I angioedema like anaphylaxis \u2014 epinephrine and antihistamines won't work well because the mechanism is bradykinin, not histamine",
      "Restarting the ACE-I or switching to another ACE-I \u2014 these patients must NEVER receive any ACE-I again",
      "Assuming ARBs are safe \u2014 5-10% cross-reactivity; many experts avoid ARBs in ACE-I angioedema patients",
      "Not preparing for difficult airway \u2014 if intubation is needed, the swelling makes it extremely challenging; have surgical airway ready",
      "Attributing first episode to 'allergic reaction' and missing that the ACE-I is the cause",
      "Not observing long enough \u2014 ACE-I angioedema can worsen over 24-48 hours even after stopping the drug"
    ],
