    "keyLearningPoints": [
      "PAIN OUT OF PROPORTION TO EXAM is the hallmark of mesenteric ischemia \u2014 severe pain with initially benign abdominal exam",
      "SMA embolism is the most common cause (50%) \u2014 typically from AFib or LV thrombus",
      "Classic timeline: sudden severe pain \u2192 gut emptying (diarrhea) \u2192 'pain-free' interval (mucosa infarcted, nerves die) \u2192 peritonitis (transmural necrosis \u2014 LATE AND OMINOUS)",
      "Lactate is the most useful lab marker \u2014 but normal lactate does NOT rule out early ischemia",
      "CTA is the diagnostic gold standard \u2014 sensitivity >95% for SMA occlusion",
      "Treatment: anticoagulation immediately, then emergent revascularization (open embolectomy or endovascular) \u00b1 bowel resection if necrotic"
    ],
    "mustNotMiss": [
      "Bowel necrosis with perforation (pneumatosis, portal venous gas, free air = dead bowel \u2014 surgery, not endovascular)",
      "Non-occlusive mesenteric ischemia (NOMI \u2014 low-flow state without vessel occlusion, seen in ICU patients on pressors)",
      "Mesenteric venous thrombosis (subacute presentation, younger patients, hypercoagulable states)",
      "Aortic dissection extending to SMA (back pain + abdominal pain + SMA malperfusion)",
      "Concurrent cardiac thrombus (AFib + recent MI = high risk \u2014 echocardiogram needed)"
    ],
    "commonPitfalls": [
      "Diagnosing 'gastroenteritis' or 'pancreatitis' in elderly patient with AFib and severe abdominal pain \u2014 always consider mesenteric ischemia",
      "Being reassured by a soft abdomen \u2014 pain out of proportion to exam is the CLASSIC early finding; peritonitis is a LATE sign",
      "Delaying CTA for plain films \u2014 X-rays are normal in >25% of mesenteric ischemia cases",
      "Not measuring lactate serially \u2014 a rising lactate indicates progression toward necrosis",
      "Waiting for 'peritoneal signs' before consulting surgery \u2014 by the time peritonitis develops, bowel is often unsalvageable",
      "Not anticoagulating immediately \u2014 heparin prevents clot propagation (use argatroban if HIT history)"
    ],
