    "keyLearningPoints": [
      "Heat stroke = core temp >104\u00b0F (40\u00b0C) + CNS DYSFUNCTION (confusion, seizure, coma). AMS is what distinguishes heat stroke from heat exhaustion.",
      "COOL FIRST, TREAT SECOND \u2014 aggressive cooling is the single most important intervention. Target <102.2\u00b0F (39\u00b0C) within 30 minutes.",
      "Cold water immersion (CWI) is the gold standard \u2014 immerse to neck in ice water bath. Cooling rate: 0.15-0.35\u00b0C/minute. This is far superior to ice packs, evaporative cooling, or cold IV fluids alone.",
      "Exertional heat stroke (young, healthy, exercising) vs. Classic heat stroke (elderly, medications, no exertion) \u2014 exertional has higher rhabdomyolysis and DIC rates.",
      "Monitor for DIC (liver failure produces coagulopathy), rhabdomyolysis with AKI, hepatic failure (peaks 48-72h), and ARDS.",
      "Stop cooling at 102\u00b0F (38.9\u00b0C) to avoid overshoot hypothermia."
    ],
    "mustNotMiss": [
      "DIC (prolonged PT, dropping fibrinogen, thrombocytopenia \u2014 massive transfusion protocol if bleeding)",
      "Hepatic failure (AST/ALT peaking 48-72 hours \u2014 can require liver transplant in severe cases)",
      "Rhabdomyolysis with AKI (CK >50,000 = high risk \u2014 aggressive IVF, target UOP 200-300mL/hr)",
      "Hyponatremic encephalopathy (exercise-associated hyponatremia from overhydration \u2014 check sodium before giving IV fluids)",
      "Cardiac arrhythmia (hyperthermia + electrolyte derangements + prolonged QTc)",
      "Meningitis/Encephalitis (fever + AMS \u2014 consider LP if not improving with cooling)"
    ],
    "commonPitfalls": [
      "Using tepid water instead of cold/ice water \u2014 evidence strongly supports cold water immersion for fastest cooling",
      "Stopping cooling before reaching target (<102\u00b0F) because the patient 'looks better'",
      "Not measuring RECTAL temperature \u2014 oral, axillary, and temporal readings are inaccurate in heat stroke",
      "Giving antipyretics (acetaminophen, NSAIDs) \u2014 these DO NOT work in heat stroke (thermoregulatory failure, not pyrogen-mediated)",
      "Not checking liver function initially and at 48-72 hours \u2014 hepatic failure is delayed and can be fatal",
      "Failing to anticipate DIC \u2014 serial coagulation studies are mandatory"
    ],
