    "keyLearningPoints": [
      "'No one is dead until they are WARM and dead' \u2014 do not declare death in hypothermic patients until rewarmed to >89.6\u00b0F (32\u00b0C) and still pulseless. Cold is neuroprotective.",
      "Severe hypothermia (<82.4\u00b0F/28\u00b0C): core rewarming required \u2014 warm IV fluids (104\u00b0F/40\u00b0C), forced warm air (Bair Hugger), and if pulseless or hemodynamically unstable \u2192 ECMO/cardiopulmonary bypass (most effective rewarming method)",
      "Handle GENTLY \u2014 rough handling can trigger lethal ventricular fibrillation in the cold, irritable myocardium",
      "Osborn (J) waves on ECG are pathognomonic for hypothermia \u2014 they resolve with rewarming",
      "If pulseless: CPR + defibrillation (one attempt if <86\u00b0F; may withhold further shocks until >86\u00b0F as cold myocardium is resistant). Rewarm to >86\u00b0F before repeated defibrillation.",
      "ACLS medications are ineffective in severe hypothermia \u2014 the heart is too cold to respond. Focus on rewarming."
    ],
    "mustNotMiss": [
      "Underlying cause of exposure (trauma with immobility, overdose, stroke, hypoglycemia, sepsis, MI \u2014 all can lead to environmental exposure)",
      "Cardiac arrest from VFib (handle gently, have defibrillator ready, be prepared for ECMO)",
      "Frostbite (this patient has bilateral toe and finger involvement \u2014 do NOT rewarm frostbitten extremities until rewarming can be sustained and core temp is improving)",
      "Aspiration pneumonia (obtunded + alcohol + outdoor exposure = aspiration risk)",
      "Rhabdomyolysis during rewarming (CK will rise \u2014 aggressive IV fluids)",
      "Rewarming afterdrop (core temp may transiently DECREASE as cold peripheral blood returns to core \u2014 anticipate and monitor)"
    ],
    "commonPitfalls": [
      "Declaring death in a hypothermic patient \u2014 'not dead until warm and dead'",
      "Aggressively handling the patient (log-rolling, rough movement) \u2014 can trigger VFib",
      "Using only external rewarming for severe hypothermia \u2014 need ACTIVE INTERNAL rewarming (warm IV fluids, warm humidified O2, consider ECMO)",
      "Not checking for underlying cause \u2014 hypothermia may be the PRESENTATION of another emergency (overdose, DKA, sepsis, stroke)",
      "Trusting pulse oximetry \u2014 it's unreliable in severe vasoconstriction; rely on clinical assessment and ABG",
      "Not monitoring potassium closely during rewarming \u2014 rapid shifts in K+ during rewarming can cause arrhythmias"
    ],
