    "keyLearningPoints": [
      "PTA is the most common deep space infection of the head and neck \u2014 typically follows inadequately treated tonsillitis/pharyngitis",
      "Classic presentation: unilateral sore throat + trismus + 'hot potato' voice + uvular deviation AWAY from the affected side + ipsilateral ear pain",
      "Drainage is the definitive treatment \u2014 needle aspiration (can be done bedside, 90%+ success) or incision and drainage. Antibiotics alone are insufficient.",
      "Antibiotic choice: amoxicillin-clavulanate (Augmentin) or ampicillin-sulbactam IV. This patient has C. diff history with clindamycin \u2014 avoid clindamycin, use metronidazole if anaerobic coverage needed.",
      "AIRWAY is the #1 concern \u2014 assess for stridor, drooling, inability to handle secretions. If airway compromise: do NOT attempt blind intubation (distorted anatomy) \u2014 awake fiberoptic or surgical airway.",
      "Complications: airway obstruction, parapharyngeal/retropharyngeal space extension, Lemierre syndrome (septic thrombophlebitis of internal jugular vein), mediastinitis"
    ],
    "mustNotMiss": [
      "Retropharyngeal abscess (posterior pharyngeal wall swelling \u2014 can compromise airway more rapidly and tracks to mediastinum)",
      "Ludwig angina (bilateral submandibular space infection with floor-of-mouth elevation \u2014 airway emergency)",
      "Lemierre syndrome (septic IJV thrombophlebitis \u2014 look for neck swelling, rigors, septic pulmonary emboli on CXR; Fusobacterium necrophorum)",
      "Epiglottitis (adult \u2014 drooling, muffled voice, but supraglottic rather than tonsillar)",
      "Peritonsillar cellulitis vs. abscess (cellulitis = no fluctuance, may respond to antibiotics alone; abscess = requires drainage)"
    ],
    "commonPitfalls": [
      "Not assessing the airway first \u2014 PTA can cause acute airway obstruction, especially with bilateral disease or parapharyngeal extension",
      "Diagnosing 'pharyngitis' without examining for asymmetry \u2014 unilateral findings with trismus are PTA until proven otherwise",
      "Attempting drainage without adequate preparation \u2014 have suction ready, patient upright, and be prepared for aspiration of pus into the airway",
      "Not checking for Lemierre syndrome on CT \u2014 always look at the internal jugular vein for thrombosis",
      "Discharging without ENT follow-up \u2014 recurrence rate is 10-15% without interval tonsillectomy",
      "Missing the trismus \u2014 failure to open the mouth adequately limits the oropharyngeal exam; CT helps when exam is limited"
    ],
